brevis, and abductor digiti minimi"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eabductor hallucis, flexor digitorum brevis, and abductor digiti minimi\u003C/strong\u003E form the first and most superficial layer of the plantar muscles of the foot (image). These muscles lie immediately deep to the plantar aponeurosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent deeper layers:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDorsal interossei muscles\u003C/strong\u003E are located on the dorsal aspect of the foot between the metatarsals\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQuadratus plantae and lumbricals\u003C/strong\u003E form the second layer of plantar muscles\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlantar interossei muscles\u003C/strong\u003E are located in the fourth (deepest) layer\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexor hallucis brevis and adductor hallucis\u003C/strong\u003E are found in the third layer\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe first layer muscles have important functions: abductor hallucis abducts and flexes the great toe, flexor digitorum brevis flexes toes two to five, and abductor digiti minimi abducts and flexes the little toe.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The intrinsic muscles of the foot are arranged in four layers on the plantar surface.","The first (most superficial) layer contains abductor hallucis, flexor digitorum brevis, and abductor digiti minimi.","These first layer muscles lie immediately deep to the plantar aponeurosis and contribute to toe flexion and abduction."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cIntrinsic Muscles of the Foot\u201d by OpenStax College\u00a0is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:1124_Intrinsic_Muscles_of_the_Foot_b.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61830"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18513"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21417"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21417"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ho2Hik5kh3EoVHddofSIn2R3URr8K8.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ho2Hik5kh3EoVHddofSIn2R3URr8K8.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":614}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61830"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T03:46:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T03:47:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11242"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76321"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifyi